```
function lengthOfLongestSubstring(s) {
  let maxLength = 0;
  let start = 0;
  const charMap = new Map();
  for (let i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
    const char = s[i];
    if (charMap.has(char) && charMap.get(char) >= start) {
      start = charMap.get(char) + 1;
    }
    charMap.set(char, i);
    maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, i - start + 1);
  }
  return maxLength;
}
```
This function uses a sliding window approach to keep track of the longest substring without repeating characters. We use a hash table (implemented as a `Map`) to keep track of the most recent index of each character we've seen. If we encounter a character that we've seen before and its most recent index is within our current substring, we move the start of the substring to the index after the last occurrence of that character. We update the hash table with the new index of the character and calculate the length of the current substring.
The time complexity of this solution is O(n) because we only iterate through the input string once. The space complexity is O(min(n, m)), where n is the length of the input string and m is the size of the character set, because we store at most one entry for each character in the hash table.

